There's options but for alot of the Xr's buyers it won't be their first iPhone therefore they're already locked in Apple's Ecosystem in a way. 
The Xr will sell no matter how many people complain because Apple is the only distributer of iOS Software and if you want a modern looking, up-to-date new iPhone for less than a thousand bucks there's only the Xr as an option (Given you're set on buying directly from Apple otherwise fuck the Xr get the X from last year)"

"The pixel to RAM ratio is the best in the iPhone XR compared to all new iPhones. (1125 x 2436 pixels)/(828 x 1792 pixels)=1.85. (4 GB RAM)/(3 GB RAM)=1.33. (4 GB RAM)/(1125 x 2436 pixels)=1.45959E-06 for XS vs (3 GB RAM)/(828 x 1792 pixels)=2.02187E-06 for XR. So the XR has the highest amount of RAM per pixel, the processors being identical. This would make XR the fastest (new) iPhone (especially for graphical applications) and this might explain the higher expected battery life, as less processing power would be used to reuse the RAM."

"The new \"Skittle\" phones!  No thanks!  I have an iPhone 6 Plus that I upgraded after owning the iPhone 4 for many years!  Like my iPhone 4, my 6 plus is in mint condition both cosmetically and in functionality. I tuned into your channel because I trust you to provide an honest overview and commentary, and you surely didn't disappoint, my friend. After watching this, I will hang on to my phone for as long as it'll go. It's crazy, I'm looking at my phone and the display and speed of function is still, after 4 bloody years, remarkably fast! The display is solid and the battery life is still great!  I just don't see myself trading my phone in order to upgrade to something that is just slightly better. When I purchased the 6 plus one of the key selling features was that it had the same computing power of putting together thousands of standard computers until it measured the size of Arizona!  The other brag was that it had more computing power than the computers that sent all of the early NASA space missions that went to the moon and orbited space; COMBINED!  How are these still not a good things? You might be right and these phones could be Apple's bread and butter, most tech reviewers seem to think the same thing, but even with this being the consensus, I think that I will just stick with my iPhone 6 Plus until it dies, I lose it, I break it, or I die; which ever comes first!  I do think that there is a good chance that this phone can tank because why would I pay for this phone when the new Samsung gives me just about everything that the 10S Max has at a low price than these new Skittle phones? Well, I might change my my mind when I see it and test it for myself, but I sincerely doubt it. These phones simply cost too much now so Apple is making my decision easier. I don't even think it's a matter of affordability anymore, buying one of these phones, even if you can afford it, just puts one's judgement in question! Anyway, thanks for the review!"

That is what makes Apple the company that sells the most loved phone in the world. What's the need for all those extra pixels? Are they really useful or just an attempt to create pseudo-superior phones for a cheaper price? I for one am really impressed with the amount of human eagles out there who claim to see the difference between a 326ppi display and anything that\u2019s above that (on a relatively small screen). Realistically though, a higher resolution only makes sense for VR applications, doesn't it? Apparently the big bad villain Apple has again released an overpriced phone (as always, with too little upgrades). Would you please do a video on this? I'd really appreciate it :) thanks"

"This actually isn't bad. The S9 and the XR are both basically the same price so most people will probably be comparing the two:

XR pro's:
-Optimisation
-7nm CPU
-50% faster GPU
-4k 60fps recording
-1080p 60fps front facing video
-portrait mode with 1 camera with all the extra studio lighting modes too
-portrait mode also on front facing camera
-iOS which is key for many buyers
-will likely see support for 4 years plus
-larger display
-face ID
-Amazing UX
-COMES IN RED


XR con's:
-No headphone jack
-Bigger bezel
-820p at 330ppi
-LCD

S9 pro's:
-headphone jack
-960fps
-Android key for other buyers
-more customisable 
-no notch
-AMOLED 
-2K max resolution
-expandable storage

S9 con's:
-previous gen CPU
-Barely got the latest version of android
-Will likely have little support 
-No portrait mode or smart lighting 
-Screen defaults to 1080p
-smaller display
-OS lags often
-Poor speakers

Honestly, there's not much between them, considering they're basically the same price, the only big thing that sticks out from the XR is the 820p display, which is basically just 720p. Which absolutely shouldn't matter on a technical level for most people, considering my internet can barely handle 1080p video streaming. The XZ premium and XZ2 premium both have 4k displays, yet no one complains when the s9+ only has a max of 2k, set to 1080p by default. While I love the larger resolutions, with the limitations of internet connections that aren't exceptional, and the fact that a phone display is smaller than a monitor, 820p isn't that bad. Especially considering that apart from the display, the XR is better than the s9 in almost every other way."

They invest so heavily into marketing, (more than anyone else) that they've essentially been able to capitalize on the common ignorance of the general public with regards to technology. As a phone salesman, I've shocked many customers when I tell them that other phones can send and receive messages via the internet and make videocalls, not just the iPhones. Their software functions in a similar way. It's very basic and easy to use in the way most people use their phones, but is extremely restrictive when it comes to customization and troubleshooting.
